{"title_page": "Al-Mulk", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Q67|the bus service|Q67 (New York City bus)}}\n{{infobox surah\n| number         = 67\n| number-3       = 067\n| name           = Surah Al-Mulk\n| name-ar        = \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643\n| name-en        = The Dominion\n| prev_sura      = At-Tahrim\n| next_sura      = Al-Qalam\n| classification = Meccan\n| othernames     = Kingship\n| juz            = 29 Tab\u0101raka -lladhi\n| rukus          = 2\n| verses         = 30\n| words          = 337\n| letters        = 1316\n| Muqattaat      = <!-- only if applicable -->\n| Sajdahs        = <!-- only if applicable -->\n| Audio          = <!-- optional, if exists -->\n}}\n{{Quran}}\n'''S\u016brat al-Mulk''' ({{lang-ar|\u0633\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643}}, \"[[Sovereignty]], Kingdom\") is the 67th chapter ([[surah]]) of the [[Quran]], comprising 30 [[ayat|verses]].<ref>[http://www.sacred-texts.com/isl/pick/067.htm Al-Mulk at Sacred Texts]</ref> The surah emphasizes that no individual can impose his will on another; he may only guide and set an example (67:26).<ref>Guppy, Shusha, ''For the good of Islam'' [[The Observer]], 15 December 1991</ref>\n\nMama always told me\nThat I was too naive\nGave away my trust for pennies\nI said don't you worry\nDidn't think that I'd be\nBroken down and crying\n\"Help me\"\nWrecked? Check\nHeart? In debt\nAll you do is come around\nJust came here to collect\nWrecked? Check\nHeart? In debt\nDon't you know that\nI cried tears of gold for you\nI sit here poor for you\nCollect my pennies and my dimes\nThat's why you love it when I cry\nPlatinum love for you\nI'd give no less for you\nGenerosity's my enemy\nSo I'm broke and\nYour heart's rich because of me\nKnow that this is my fault\nGave a little too much\nKnew that this was gonna happen\nBut I'm not gonna lie\nYou can make me cry, thousand times\nI come running back like\n\"What is going on with my head?\"\nWrecked? Check\nHeart? In debt\nAll you do is come around\nJust came here to collect\nWrecked? Check\nHeart? In debt\nDon't you know that\nI cried tears of gold for you\nI sit here poor for you\nCollect my pennies and my dimes\nThat's why you love it when I cry\nPlatinum love for you\nI'd give no less for you\nGenerosity's my enemy\nSo I'm broke and\nYour heart's rich because of me\nAnd the worst part is I'd do it all over again\nThe worst part is, I know it's never gonna end\nI keep coming right back like a maniac\nI keep coming right back like\nAnd the worst part is I'd do it all over again\nNo, the worst part is I know it's never gonna end\nI keep coming right back like a maniac\nI cried tears of gold for you\nI sit here poor for you\nCollect my pennies and my dimes\nThat's why you love it when I cry\nPlatinum love for you\nI'd give no less for you\nGenerosity's my enemy\nSo I'm broke and\nYour heart's rich because of me\n\n==Placement & Coherence with other surahs==\nThe idea of textual relation between the verses of a chapter has been discussed under various titles such as ''nazm'' and ''munasabah'' in non-English literature and ''coherence'', ''text relations'', ''intertextuality'', and ''unity'' in English literature. [[Hamiduddin Farahi]], an [[Islamic]] scholar of the [[Indian subcontinent]], is known for his work on the concept of nazm, or coherence, in the Quran. [[Fakhruddin al-Razi]] (died 1209 CE),  Zarkashi (died 1392) and several other classical as well as contemporary Quranic scholars have contributed to the studies.<ref name=farrahi>{{cite book|last=[[Hamiduddin Farahi]]|first=translated by Tariq Mahmood Hashmi|title=Exordium to coherence in the Quran : an English translation of F\u0101ti\u1e25ah Ni\u1e93\u0101m al-Qur\u02bc\u0101n|year=2008|publisher=al-Mawrid|location=Lahore|isbn=9698799575|edition=1st}}</ref> This surah belongs to the last(7th) group of surahs which starts from Surah [[Al-Mulk]] (67) and runs till the end of the Quran. According to [[Javed Ahmad Ghamidi]] {{quote|The theme of this group is Warning the leadership of the Quraysh of the consequences of the Hereafter, and delivering glad tidings to Muhammad (sws) of the supremacy of the truth in Arabia. This theme gradually reaches its culmination through the arrangement of various surahs in this group.<ref name =\"ghamdi\">[[Javed Ahmad Ghamidi]]</ref><ref>https://www.javedahmedghamidi.org/#!/quran-home</ref>\n}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Phase !! From !! To !! Central theme\n|-\n| I || [[Al-Mulk]] {{quran-usc|67|1}} || [[Al-Jinn]] {{quran-usc|72|1}} || Indhar (Warning)\n|-\n| II || [[Al-Muzzammil]] {{quran-usc|73|1}} || [[Al-Inshirah]] {{quran-usc|94|1}} || Indhar-i \u2018am (Augmented Warning)\n|-\n| III || [[At-Tin]] {{quran-usc|95|1}} || [[Quraysh (surah)]] {{quran-usc|106|1}} || Itmam al-Hujjah (Conclusive Communication of the Truth)\n|-\n| IV || [[Al-Ma'un]] {{quran-usc|107|1}} || [[Al-Ikhlas]] {{quran-usc|112|1}} || Hijrah and Bara\u2019ah (Migration and Acquittal)\n|-\n| V || [[Al-Falaq]] {{quran-usc|113|1}} || [[Al-Nas]] {{quran-usc|114|1}} || The Conclusion/The End\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LfH1Yz_3aMY/ Best Real time Visualization of Surah Mulk with English translation, for non-Muslims]\n*[https://myislam.org/surah-al-mulk/ Read Surah Al Mulk With Full English Translation]\n{{Sura|67|[[At-Tahrim]]|[[Al-Qalam]]}}\n\n[[Category:Chapters in the Quran|Mulk]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Q67|the bus service|Q67 (New York City bus)}}\n{{infobox surah\n| number         = 67\n| number-3       = 067\n| name           = Surah Al-Mulk\n| name-ar        = \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643\n| name-en        = The Dominion\n| prev_sura      = At-Tahrim\n| next_sura      = Al-Qalam\n| classification = Meccan\n| othernames     = Kingship\n| juz            = 29 Tab\u0101raka -lladhi\n| rukus          = 2\n| verses         = 30\n| words          = 337\n| letters        = 1316\n| Muqattaat      = <!-- only if applicable -->\n| Sajdahs        = <!-- only if applicable -->\n| Audio          = <!-- optional, if exists -->\n}}\n{{Quran}}\n'''S\u016brat al-Mulk''' ({{lang-ar|\u0633\u0648\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643}}, \"[[Sovereignty]], Kingdom\") is the 67th chapter ([[surah]]) of the [[Quran]], comprising 30 [[ayat|verses]].<ref>[http://www.sacred-texts.com/isl/pick/067.htm Al-Mulk at Sacred Texts]</ref> The surah emphasizes that no individual can impose his will on another; he may only guide and set an example (67:26).<ref>Guppy, Shusha, ''For the good of Islam'' [[The Observer]], 15 December 1991</ref>\n\n==Hadith==\nThe first and foremost [[exegesis]]/[[tafsir]] of the [[Qur'an]] is found in hadith of [[Muhammad]]<ref>[[Tafsir#Muhammad]]</ref><ref>\u015eatibi, El-muvafakat</ref> and while [[hadith]] is literally \"speech\"; recorded saying or tradition of [[Muhammad]]\ufdfa validated by [[isnad]]; with [[Sirat Rasul Allah|seerah]] these comprise the [[sunnah]] and reveal [[shariah]] and [[tafsir]]. Although scholars including [[ibn Taymiyyah]] claim that Muhammad\ufdfa has commented on the whole of the Qur'an, others including [[Ghazali]] cite the limited amount of [[hadith|narratives]], thus indicating that he has commented only on a portion of the Qur'an.<ref>Muhsin Demirci, Tefsir Usul\u00fc, 120</ref> In either the case, higher count of hadith elevates the importance of the pertinent surah from a certain perspective. This surah holds special place in the sayings as well as practices of Muhammad\ufdfa, which can be observed by these related ahadith.\n\n* [[Ahmad ibn Hanbal|Imam Ahmad]] recorded from [[Abu Hurayrah]] that Muhammad\ufdfa said,\"Verily, there is a chapter in the Qur'an which contains thirty Ayat that will intercede on behalf of its reciter until he is forgiven. (It is): 'Blessed be He in Whose Hand is the dominion. (Surah Al-Mulk 67)'\"<ref>[This Hadith was collected by At-Tirmidhi and the four Sunan Compilers. At-Tirmidhi said concerning it, \"This is a [[Hadith terminology#\u1e24asan|Hasan Hadith]].]</ref><ref>([[Jami` at-Tirmidhi]] Hadith 2891) Imaam [[at-Tirmidhi]] has classified this narration as Hasan (sound) and Imaam [[Ibn Hibban]] and [[Abu Abdullah al-Hakim Nishapuri]] regarded it as Sahih (authentic). See Saheeh ibn Hibbaan vol. 3,  p. 67-69 and [[Al-Mustadrak alaa al-Sahihain]] vol. 2, p. 498</ref><ref>[[Abu Dawood]], [[Ahmad ibn Hanbal|Imam Ahmad]], [[at-Tirmidhi]], Riyad as-Salihin by Imam [[Al-Nawawi]] Ch.183 #1016</ref>\n* Muhammad\ufdfa said, 'There is a [[surah]] in the Qur'an which is only thirty verses. It defends whoever recites it until it puts him into [[Jannah]]'<ref>Fath al Qadir 5/257, Sahihul Jamiea 1/680, Tabrani in Al-Awsat & Ibn Mardawaith</ref>\n* [[Anas ibn Malik]] reported Muhammad\ufdfa as saying, \"There is a Surah which will plead for its reciter till it causes him to enter paradise.\"<ref>[[Al-Tabarani]]</ref>\n* Muhammad\ufdfa said, 'Surah al Mulk is the protector from the torment of the grave'<ref>Sahihul Jamiea 1/680, [[Abu Abdullah al-Hakim Nishapuri]] - [[Al-Mustadrak alaa al-Sahihain]] 2/498 & [[Al-Nasa'i]]</ref>\n* Jabir said it was the custom of not to go to sleep until he had read Tabarakalladhi Biyadihil Mulk(Al-Mulk) and Alif Laam Meem Tanzeel ([[As-Sajda]]).<ref>Ahmad, Tirmidhi and [[Sunan al-Darimi]]</ref>\n* He used to recite Surah As-Sajdah and Surah Al-Mulk (in Arabic) before sleeping.<ref>At-Tirmithi, An-Nasa'i. See also Al-Albani, Sahihul-Jami As-Saghir 4/255</ref>\n* Abdullah Ibn 'Abbas reported that Muhammad\ufdfa said, 'It is my desire/love that Surahtul Mulk should be in the heart of every Muslim'<ref>[Hakim, al-Hisnul Haseen by the classical scholar Muhammad\ufdfa al-Jazri]</ref>\n* [[Ibn Abbas]] said that one of Muhammad\ufdfa's companions set up his tent over a grave without realising that it was a grave and it contained a man who was reciting the Surah Tabarakalladhi Biyadihil Mulk up to the end. He went and told Muhammad\ufdfa who said, 'It is The Defender; it is The Protector which safeguards from Allah Ta'ala's Punishment'<ref>[[at-Tirmidhi]]</ref>\n* Khalid bin Madam said about surat Al Mulk and [[As-Sajda]] that these two surahs will fight for their reciter in the grave and will say, 'O Allah! If we belong to Your book, accept our intercession in his favour. In case we do not, get us obliterated. These surahs will spread their wings like birds and will save the person from the torment of the grave.'<ref>Mishkat al-Misbah</ref>\n* It was narrated that [[Abd Allah ibn Mas'ud]] said: Whoever reads Tabarakalladhi Biyadihil Mulk [i.e. Surah al-Mulk] every night, Allah will protect him from the torment of the grave. At the time of the Messenger of Allah, we used to call it al-mani'ah (that which protects). In the Book of [[Allah]] it is a surah which, whoever recites it every night has done very well.<ref>[[Al-Nasa'i]]</ref><ref>[Sahih at-Targhib wat-Tarhib, no. 1475]</ref>\n* [[Abdullah ibn Masud]] is reported to have said, 'A man will be approached in his grave from his legs and from his chest and then from his head. And each time this Surah will defend him by saying, 'You cannot do anything to him, he used to recite Surah Mulk'.'\n* [[Abdullah ibn Masud]] further states, 'It is called, 'Al-maani'ah'. For it protects from the punishment of the [[grave]].'<ref>(Mustadrak al-Haakim vol.2, p. 498). [[Abu Abdullah al-Hakim Nishapuri]] has classified this narration as [[Hadith terminology#\u1e62a\u1e25\u012b\u1e25|Saheeh]] (authentic) and Haafiz Zahabiy has confirmed this.</ref>\n* [[Ibn Umar]] said that once that [[Muhammad]]\ufdfa recited verse 2 (the One Who created death and life so that He may test you as to which of you is better in deeds) and when he reached the words \"better in deeds\", he stopped and explained that 'better in deeds' is the person who abstains most from the things [[Allah]] has forbidden and is always ready to obey Him.\"\n* Yahya related to me from Malik from Ibn Shihab that Humayd ibn Abd ar-Rahman ibn Awf had told him that Surat al-Ikhlas (Sura 112) was equal to a third of the Qur'an, and that Surat al-mulk (Sura 67) pleaded for its owner.<ref>[[Imam Malik]]'s Muwatta Chapter No: 15, The Quran, Hadith no: 19 Narrated by [[Imam Malik]]</ref>\n\n==Placement & Coherence with other surahs==\nThe idea of textual relation between the verses of a chapter has been discussed under various titles such as ''nazm'' and ''munasabah'' in non-English literature and ''coherence'', ''text relations'', ''intertextuality'', and ''unity'' in English literature. [[Hamiduddin Farahi]], an [[Islamic]] scholar of the [[Indian subcontinent]], is known for his work on the concept of nazm, or coherence, in the Quran. [[Fakhruddin al-Razi]] (died 1209 CE),  Zarkashi (died 1392) and several other classical as well as contemporary Quranic scholars have contributed to the studies.<ref name=farrahi>{{cite book|last=[[Hamiduddin Farahi]]|first=translated by Tariq Mahmood Hashmi|title=Exordium to coherence in the Quran : an English translation of F\u0101ti\u1e25ah Ni\u1e93\u0101m al-Qur\u02bc\u0101n|year=2008|publisher=al-Mawrid|location=Lahore|isbn=9698799575|edition=1st}}</ref> This surah belongs to the last(7th) group of surahs which starts from Surah [[Al-Mulk]] (67) and runs till the end of the Quran. According to [[Javed Ahmad Ghamidi]] {{quote|The theme of this group is Warning the leadership of the Quraysh of the consequences of the Hereafter, and delivering glad tidings to Muhammad (sws) of the supremacy of the truth in Arabia. This theme gradually reaches its culmination through the arrangement of various surahs in this group.<ref name =\"ghamdi\">[[Javed Ahmad Ghamidi]]</ref><ref>https://www.javedahmedghamidi.org/#!/quran-home</ref>\n}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Phase !! From !! To !! Central theme\n|-\n| I || [[Al-Mulk]] {{quran-usc|67|1}} || [[Al-Jinn]] {{quran-usc|72|1}} || Indhar (Warning)\n|-\n| II || [[Al-Muzzammil]] {{quran-usc|73|1}} || [[Al-Inshirah]] {{quran-usc|94|1}} || Indhar-i \u2018am (Augmented Warning)\n|-\n| III || [[At-Tin]] {{quran-usc|95|1}} || [[Quraysh (surah)]] {{quran-usc|106|1}} || Itmam al-Hujjah (Conclusive Communication of the Truth)\n|-\n| IV || [[Al-Ma'un]] {{quran-usc|107|1}} || [[Al-Ikhlas]] {{quran-usc|112|1}} || Hijrah and Bara\u2019ah (Migration and Acquittal)\n|-\n| V || [[Al-Falaq]] {{quran-usc|113|1}} || [[Al-Nas]] {{quran-usc|114|1}} || The Conclusion/The End\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LfH1Yz_3aMY/ Best Real time Visualization of Surah Mulk with English translation, for non-Muslims]\n*[https://myislam.org/surah-al-mulk/ Read Surah Al Mulk With Full English Translation]\n{{Sura|67|[[At-Tahrim]]|[[Al-Qalam]]}}\n\n[[Category:Chapters in the Quran|Mulk]]\n", "name_user": "87.200.150.29", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I m not sure)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Mulk"}
{"title_page": "Boeing Starliner Spacecraft 3", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{linkrot|date=April 2020}}{{primary sources|date=April 2020}}}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Space Shuttle\n| name = Calypso <br> Spacecraft 3\n| image = [[File:Calypso Starliner capsule postflight.jpg|250px]]\n| caption = Calypso undergoing post flight processing following it's maiden flight.\n| number =\n| country = United States\n| contract =\n| named_after = [[RV Calypso]]\n| first_flight = [[Boe-OFT]]\n| first_date = 20 December 2019\n| last_flight =\n| last_date =\n| next_date = NET October 2020\n| missions = 1\n| crews =\n| time = 2d, 1h, 22m, 10s\n| distance =\n| deployed =\n| dockings_mir =\n| dockings_iss =0\n| status = In service\n}}\n\n'''Boeing Starliner spacecraft 3''', also known as '''Calypso''' is a [[Boeing CST-100 Starliner]] spacecraft built on operated by [[Boeing]] on behalf of [[NASA]] under the [[Commercial Crew Program]]. On 20 December 2019 Calypso launched on the [[Boe-OFT|Boeing-Orbital Flight Test]] mission, an uncrewed test flight of Starliner to the International Space Station.<ref>https://www.rocketlaunch.live/launch/cst-100-oft</ref>. The spacecraft was scheduled to dock to the ISS and then return to Earth following a week in space, although due to several software issues the spacecraft was unable to rendezvous with the station and landed following two days in space, this resulted in Boeing needing to schedule a second Orbital Flight Test which is currently targeted for October 2020<ref>https://blogs.nasa.gov/commercialcrew/2020/04/06/boeing-to-fly-second-uncrewed-orbital-flight-test-for-nasa/</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn September 2014 Boeing was one of two companies selected by NASA to develop crewed spacecraft to ferry astronauts to the [[International Space Station]], the other being [[SpaceX]]. Boeing planned to construct three Starliner spacecraft, the spacecraft's ability to be reused up to ten times with a six-month turn around time in between flights meant three spacecraft would be enough to satisfy the needs to the Commercial Crew Program<ref>https://www.boeing.com/space/starliner/</ref>.\n\n[[File:CST-100 Starliner spacecraft KSC-20180426-PH BOE01 0003~orig.jpg|right|thumb|Calypso under construction.]]\n\nSpacecraft 3 launched for the first time on Boe-OFT, the first orbital flight of Starliner, on 20 December 2019. The spacecraft was scheduled to dock with the ISS the following day, although, due to software error with the spacecraft's Mission Elapsed Timer (MET) causing the spacecraft's internal timer to be off by 11 hours resulted in the spacecraft performing on \"off-nominal orbital insertion burn\" and barred the spacecraft from being able to rendezvous and dock with the ISS during the flight<ref>https://blogs.nasa.gov/commercialcrew/2020/02/07/nasa-shares-initial-findings-from-boeing-starliner-orbital-flight-test-investigation/</ref>. Instead the spacecraft remained in orbit for two days, performing as many tests as possible without the ISS rendezvous, and landed at [[White Sands Missile Range]], [[New Mexico]] on 22 December 2019<ref>https://blogs.nasa.gov/commercialcrew/2019/12/22/nasa-boeing-complete-successful-landing-of-starliner-flight-test/</ref>.\n\n[[File:Boe-OFT heads toward landing.jpg|left|thumb|Calypso returning to Earth following its first flight.]]\n\nFollowing landing it was announced that the spacecraft would be reflown on [[USCV-2]], the first operational flight of Starliner to the ISS, following this announcement NASA astronaut [[Sunita Williams]], USCV-2 Commander named the spacecraft \"Calypso\" after [[Jaques Yves Costue|Jaques Yves Costue's]] [[Oceanography]] vessel, [[RV Calypso]]<ref>https://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/starliner-returns-to-earth-with-a-new-name-calypso</ref>. Calypso is currently the only Starliner spacecraft to be given an official name.\n\nAlthough Calypso is still scheduled to return to space on USCV-2, Boeing's announcement in March 2020 that they would refly the Orbital Flight Test due to the numerous problems on the first test casts some doubt on if that will actually happen since the spacecraft rotation might need to be shuffled around. The spacecraft might now return to space on [[Boe-CFT]], the first crewed test flight of Starliner. Following the spacecraft's second flight it is unclear on when Boeing or NASA will fly the spacecraft again, Boeing is currently contracted to fly five operational missions to the ISS under the Commercial Crew Program following USCV-2, so Calypso will most likely see space for a third time on a later crew rotation flight.\n\n==Flights==\nCalypso flew in space for the first time on the [[Boe-OFT]] mission on 20 December 2019, the spacecraft was scheduled to be reflown on [[USCV-2]] sometime in 2021 although the current flight scheduled currently unclear since it is unknown which spacecraft will fly the [[Boeing Orbital Flight Test 2]] mission.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Mission\n!Launch date\n(UTC)\n!Insignia\n!Crew\n!Remarks\n!Duration\n!Outcome\n|-\n| [[Boeing Orbital Flight Test|Boe-OFT]]\n| 20 December 2019, 11:36:43\n|\n| {{N/A}}\n| First uncrewed orbital test flight of Starliner. The mission's main objective of ISS rendezvous was aborted due to software incorrectly keeping mission time, leading to a late orbital insertion burn with excessive fuel expenditure.\n| 2d, 1h, 22m, 10s\n| {{partial failure}} due to two critical software defects. Rendezvous with ISS cancelled.\n|-\n| [[USCV-2]]\n| 2021 NET\n|\n| {{Flagicon|USA}} [[Sunita Williams]]<br>{{Flagicon|USA}} [[Josh Cassada]]<br>{{Flagicon|FRA}} [[Thomas Pesquet]]<br>{{Flagicon|RUS}} [[Andrei Borisenko]]\n| First operational flight of Boeing Starliner.\n| 6 Months (planned)\n| {{Planned}}\n|}\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Spacecraft]]\n\n{{Improve categories|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{linkrot|date=April 2020}}{{primary sources|date=April 2020}}}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Space Shuttle\n| name = Calypso <br> Spacecraft 3\n| image = [[File:Calypso Starliner capsule postflight.jpg|250px]]\n| caption = Calypso undergoing post flight processing following it's maiden flight.\n| number =\n| country = United States\n| contract =\n| named_after = [[RV Calypso]]\n| first_flight = [[Boe-OFT]]\n| first_date = 20 December 2019\n| last_flight =\n| last_date =\n| next_date = NET October 2020\n| missions = 1\n| crews =\n| time = 2d, 1h, 22m, 10s\n| distance =\n| deployed =\n| dockings_mir =\n| dockings_iss =0\n| status = In service\n}}\n\n'''Boeing Starliner spacecraft 3''', also known as '''Calypso''' is a [[Boeing CST-100 Starliner]] spacecraft built on operated by [[Boeing]] on behalf of [[NASA]] under the [[Commercial Crew Program]]. On 20 December 2019 Calypso launched on the [[Boe-OFT|Boeing-Orbital Flight Test]] mission, an uncrewed test flight of Starliner to the International Space Station.<ref>https://www.rocketlaunch.live/launch/cst-100-oft</ref>. The spacecraft was scheduled to dock to the ISS and then return to Earth following a week in space, although due to several software issues the spacecraft was unable to rendezvous with the station and landed following two days in space, this resulted in Boeing needed to schedule a second Orbital Flight Test which is currently targeted for October 2020<ref>https://blogs.nasa.gov/commercialcrew/2020/04/06/boeing-to-fly-second-uncrewed-orbital-flight-test-for-nasa/</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn September 2014 Boeing was one of two companies selected by NASA to develop crewed spacecraft to ferry astronauts to the [[International Space Station]], the other being [[SpaceX]]. Boeing planned to construct three Starliner spacecraft, the spacecraft's ability to be reused up to ten times with a six-month turn around time in between flights meant three spacecraft would be enough to satisfy the needs to the Commercial Crew Program<ref>https://www.boeing.com/space/starliner/</ref>.\n\n[[File:CST-100 Starliner spacecraft KSC-20180426-PH BOE01 0003~orig.jpg|right|thumb|Calypso under construction.]]\n\nSpacecraft 3 launched for the first time on Boe-OFT, the first orbital flight of Starliner, on 20 December 2019. The spacecraft was scheduled to dock with the ISS the following day, although, due to software error with the spacecraft's Mission Elapsed Timer (MET) causing the spacecraft's internal timer to be off by 11 hours resulted in the spacecraft performing on \"off-nominal orbital insertion burn\" and barred the spacecraft from being able to rendezvous and dock with the ISS during the flight<ref>https://blogs.nasa.gov/commercialcrew/2020/02/07/nasa-shares-initial-findings-from-boeing-starliner-orbital-flight-test-investigation/</ref>. Instead the spacecraft remained in orbit for two days, performing as many tests as possible without the ISS rendezvous, and landed at [[White Sands Missile Range]], [[New Mexico]] on 22 December 2019<ref>https://blogs.nasa.gov/commercialcrew/2019/12/22/nasa-boeing-complete-successful-landing-of-starliner-flight-test/</ref>.\n\n[[File:Boe-OFT heads toward landing.jpg|left|thumb|Calypso returning to Earth following its first flight.]]\n\nFollowing landing it was announced that the spacecraft would be reflown on [[USCV-2]], the first operational flight of Starliner to the ISS, following this announcement NASA astronaut [[Sunita Williams]], USCV-2 Commander named the spacecraft \"Calypso\" after [[Jaques Yves Costue|Jaques Yves Costue's]] [[Oceanography]] vessel, [[RV Calypso]]<ref>https://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/starliner-returns-to-earth-with-a-new-name-calypso</ref>. Calypso is currently the only Starliner spacecraft to be given an official name.\n\nAlthough Calypso is still scheduled to return to space on USCV-2, Boeing's announcement in March 2020 that they would refly the Orbital Flight Test due to the numerous problems on the first test casts some doubt on if that will actually happen since the spacecraft rotation might need to be shuffled around. The spacecraft might now return to space on [[Boe-CFT]], the first crewed test flight of Starliner. Following the spacecraft's second flight it is unclear on when Boeing or NASA will fly the spacecraft again, Boeing is currently contracted to fly five operational missions to the ISS under the Commercial Crew Program following USCV-2, so Calypso will most likely see space for a third time on a later crew rotation flight.\n\n==Flights==\nCalypso flew in space for the first time on the [[Boe-OFT]] mission on 20 December 2019, the spacecraft was scheduled to be reflown on [[USCV-2]] sometime in 2021 although the current flight scheduled currently unclear since it is unknown which spacecraft will fly the [[Boeing Orbital Flight Test 2]] mission.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Mission\n!Launch date\n(UTC)\n!Insignia\n!Crew\n!Remarks\n!Duration\n!Outcome\n|-\n| [[Boeing Orbital Flight Test|Boe-OFT]]\n| 20 December 2019, 11:36:43\n|\n| {{N/A}}\n| First uncrewed orbital test flight of Starliner. The mission's main objective of ISS rendezvous was aborted due to software incorrectly keeping mission time, leading to a late orbital insertion burn with excessive fuel expenditure.\n| 2d, 1h, 22m, 10s\n| {{partial failure}} due to two critical software defects. Rendezvous with ISS cancelled.\n|-\n| [[USCV-2]]\n| 2021 NET\n|\n| {{Flagicon|USA}} [[Sunita Williams]]<br>{{Flagicon|USA}} [[Josh Cassada]]<br>{{Flagicon|FRA}} [[Thomas Pesquet]]<br>{{Flagicon|RUS}} [[Andrei Borisenko]]\n| First operational flight of Boeing Starliner.\n| 6 Months (planned)\n| {{Planned}}\n|}\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for